ROSEBURG, Ore. -- It's Friday night. And in Roseburg, that means football. 
Friday was the first time back on the field for a game at Roseburg High School since the Umpqua Community College mass shooting on Oct. 1 . 
Football was a brief moment of normalcy for this small town that's been overwhelmed by the national spotlight. 
Rsoeburg and South Medford both paid respect to the nine victims killed in the mass shooting eight days prior with decals on their helmets. 
And the grandstands were filled with UCC T-shirts. Students sold them to raise money for the victims. 
South Medford won the game 42-13, but it didn't matter Friday night. The community showed they're Roseburg-strong.
